Example Problem. How to fit a curve to this?¶

Ordinary Least Squares in Higher Dimensions¶

Instead of scalar $x$ we want to have a K-dimensional data vectors $\{x_i\}$,

where $x_i = \begin{bmatrix} x_{i1} \\ x_{i2} \\ \vdots \\ x_{iK} \end{bmatrix}_{K \times 1}$

$$ \hat{Y_i} = \beta_0 + X_{i1} \beta_1 + X_{i2} \beta_2 + \ldots + X_{iK} \beta_K $$¶

$$\begin{bmatrix}¶

Y_1 \ Y_2 \ \vdots \ \vdots \ Y_N

\end{bmatrix}_{N\times 1}¶

\begin{bmatrix} 1 & X_{11} & X_{12} & \ldots & X_{1K}\\ 1 & X_{21} & X_{22} & \ldots & X_{2K}\\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ldots & \vdots \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ldots & \vdots \\ 1 & X_{N1} & X_{N2} & \ldots & X_{NK}\\ \end{bmatrix}

_{N\times K+1} \begin{bmatrix} \beta_0 \\ \beta_1 \\ \vdots \\ \vdots \\ \beta_K \end{bmatrix}_{K + 1\times 1} + \begin{bmatrix} \epsilon_1 \\ \epsilon_2 \\ \vdots \\ \vdots \\ \epsilon_N \end{bmatrix}_{N\times 1} $$

This can be rewritten more simply as:

$$y=X \beta +\epsilon$$¶

$y=X \beta +\epsilon$¶

$\epsilon = y - X \beta $¶

$\text{Loss} = \sum_{i=1}^{N} \epsilon_i^2 = \epsilon^T \epsilon $¶

$\text{Loss} = \epsilon^T \epsilon $

$ = (y - X \beta)^T (y - X \beta )$

$ = y^T y - y^T X \beta - \beta^T X^T y + \beta^T X^T X \beta $

Since $y^T X \beta$ is a scalar, $ y^T X \beta = (y^T X \beta)^T = \beta^T X^T y$, so

$ = y^T y - 2 \beta^T X^T y + \beta^T X^T X \beta $

$ Loss = y^T y - 2 \beta^T X^T y + \beta^T X^T X \beta $

$\frac{\partial{Loss}}{\partial{\beta}}¶

= \frac{\partial{\epsilon^T \epsilon}}{\partial{\beta}} = \frac{\partial{(y^T y - 2 \beta^T X^T y + \beta^T X^T X \beta)}}{\partial{\beta}} = -2 X^T y + 2X^T X \beta $

using $ \frac{\partial{(\beta^T Z \beta)}}{\partial{\beta}} = 2 Z \beta$ and $ \frac{\partial{\beta^T Z}}{\partial{\beta}} = Z$ See https://web.stanford.edu/~mrosenfe/soc_meth_proj3/matrix_OLS_NYU_notes.pdf for details.

Let $\hat{\beta}$ be the extermum point.

$-2 X^T y + 2X^T X \hat{\beta} = 0 $¶

$ X^T y = X^T X \hat{\beta} $¶

When $X^T X$ is invertible

$ \hat{\beta} = (X^T X)^{-1}X^T y $¶

we still need to look at the Hessian to make sure it's a minimum, but it is :)

How Multinomial is better than scalar?¶

Since X is multinomial, it can be anything, say polynomial

$$\begin{bmatrix}¶

Y_1 \ Y_2 \ \vdots \ \vdots \ Y_N

\end{bmatrix}_{N\times 1}¶

\begin{bmatrix} 1 & X_{1} & X_{1}^2 & \ldots & X_{1}^K\\ 1 & X_{1} & X_{2}^2 & \ldots & X_{2}^K\\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ldots & \vdots \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ldots & \vdots \\ 1 & X_{N} & X_{N}^2 & \ldots & X_{N}^K\\ \end{bmatrix}

_{N\times K+1} \begin{bmatrix} \beta_0 \\ \beta_1 \\ \vdots \\ \vdots \\ \beta_K \end{bmatrix}_{K + 1\times 1} + \begin{bmatrix} \epsilon_1 \\ \epsilon_2 \\ \vdots \\ \vdots \\ \epsilon_N \end{bmatrix}_{N\times 1} $$

degrees = list(range(1, 19))
losses = []
true_losses = []
for k in degrees:
    beta = fit_polynomial_regression(x, y, degree=k)
    losses.append(mean_square_loss(y_hat(x, beta), y))
    true_losses.append(mean_square_loss(y_hat(x, beta), true_func(x)))

plt.plot(degrees, losses, label='data loss')
plt.plot(degrees, true_losses, label='true loss agains f^*')

plt.xticks(degrees)
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel('Degree of Polynomial')
plt.yscale('log')
plt.ylabel('Mean Square Error');

In [119]:
def true_func(x):
    return - 0.5 * x + x ** 2 + 0.1 * x ** 3 - 0.05 * x ** 4

We assume that there is a function with noise $y = f ( x ) + $, where the noise, $\varepsilon $, has zero mean and variance $ \sigma ^{2}$

Exactly how we have modeled our generating function, let's try to understand where does the noise come from.

Bias Variance¶

Notation¶

  • ### $f^*(x)$ := true function
  • ### $\hat{\beta}$ estimate of the parameters, for $g(x, \beta)$ that we are trying to find
  • ### $\hat{f} := \hat{f}(x, \text{Data}) = g(x, \hat{\beta}) \equiv \hat{y}$ estimate of the function
  • ### $y(x) = f^*(x) + \epsilon$

We want to calculate

$\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{Data}[(y(x) - \hat{f}(x, Data))^2]$¶

$\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{Data}[(y(x) - \hat{f}(x, Data)^2]$¶

for simplicity, let's drop arguments,

$\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(y - \hat{f})^2]$

$ = \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(f^* + \epsilon - \hat{f})^2]$

add, and subtract $\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}]$

$ = \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(f^* - \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}] + \epsilon - \hat{f} + \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}] )^2]$

$ = \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[((f^* - \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}]) + \epsilon - (\hat{f} - \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}] ))^2]$

$ = \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(f^* - \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}])^2 + \epsilon^2 + (\hat{f} - \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}] )^2

  • 2\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(f^*-\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}])\epsilon]
  • 2\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(\hat{f}-\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}])\epsilon]]
  • 2\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(f^*-\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}])(\hat{f}-\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}])] $

Using $\epsilon$ is independent of of data

$ = Bias[\hat{f}]^2 + Var[\epsilon] + Var[\hat{f}]

  • 2 \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\epsilon] \left( \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(f^*-\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}]) - \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(\hat{f}-\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}]) \right)
  • 2(f^* - \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}])\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(\hat{f}-\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}])$

Using $ \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(\hat{f}-\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}] ) = \mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}]-\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\hat{f}] = 0$ , and that $\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[\epsilon] = 0 $

$\mathop{\mathbb{E}}[(y - \hat{f})^2] = Bias[\hat{f}]^2 + Var[\epsilon] + Var[\hat{f}]$¶

Gauss-Markov Theorem¶

source: https://web.stanford.edu/~mrosenfe/soc_meth_proj3/matrix_OLS_NYU_notes.pdf

Ridge Regression¶

We can we increase bias and decrease variance? $\hat{\beta}$ has zero bias

$\text{Loss} = \epsilon^T \epsilon + \lambda \beta^T \beta$

$ = y^T y - 2 \beta^T X^T y + \beta^T X^T X \beta + \lambda \beta^T \beta$

$\frac{\partial{Loss}}{\partial{\beta}}¶

= \frac{\partial{(y^T y - 2 \beta^T X^T y + \beta^T X^T X \beta + \lambda \beta^T \beta)}}{\partial{\beta}} = -2 X^T y + 2X^T X \beta + 2 \lambda \beta $

$-2 X^T y + 2X^T X \hat{\beta} + 2 \lambda \hat{\beta} = 0$

$X^T y = X^T X \hat{\beta} + \lambda \hat{\beta}$

When $X^T X + \lambda I$ is invertible

$ \hat{\beta} = (X^T X + \lambda I)^{-1}X^T y $¶

Side effect! It can even work when $X^TX$ is singular.
